elements.content: Self-assemblies of two unsymmetrical tridentate N2O/N2S donor Schiff base ligands, that is, 2-((2-(dimethylamino)ethylimino)methyl)phenol (HL 1 ) and methyl-2-pyridylmethylidenehy-drazinecarbodithioate (HL 2 ), with different cadmium salts have led to 11 anion-controlled complexes, namely, [Cd(L n )2] [n = 1 for 1 and n = 2 for 2], [Cd(L 1 )(HL 1 )](ClO4) (3), [Cd(HL 2 )(L2)](ClO4)(H2O) (4), [Cd(L2)Cl2] (5), [Cd(L1)Cl]2 (6), [Cd(L1)(NO3)]2 (7), [Cd(L2)(NO3)(CH3OH)]2 (8), [Cd(L2)(NO3)(H2O)]2 (8a), [Cd2(L1)2(SCN)2] n (9), and [CdL2(SCN)2] n (10), respectively. Eleven compounds were characterized by elemental analyses, IR spectra, MS and thermogravimetric analyses, of which 10 structures 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 8a, 9, and 10 were further determined by single-crystal X-ray diffraction analyses. The compounds 2, 3, and 4 are mononuclear, in which the neutral molecule unit CdII(L2)2 (in 2) as well as cation units [CdII(HL 1−2 )(L1−2)]+ (L1 for 3 and L2 for 4) are respectively connected by hydrogen bonds C−H···S, O−H···O, and C−H···O and form three-dimensional (3D) ordered network structures. With the replacement of Cd(CH3COO)2/Cd(ClO4)2 by CdCl2/Cd(NO3)2 in the above reactions, because of the coordination interactions of nitrate and chloride anions in these cases, the obtained corresponding compounds 6−8 present dinuclear structures with planar Cd2O2/Cd2S2 quadrilateral cores and only compound 5 mononuclear, in which the folding effect of sulfur and solvent effect, to a certain extent, affect the microstructure of these complexes, such as the arrangements of the ligand L1−2 and nitrate/chloride ions. Furthermore, through intermolecular weak interactions, for example, C−H···O, O−H···N hydrogen bonding and π···π stacking, 3D supramolecular structures are assembled in these compounds. However, reactions of Cd(CH3COO)2/Cd(ClO4)2 + KSCN with L (L = L1(9), L2(10)) yield two one-dimensional (1D) chain-like compounds, and similarly, via interchain hydrogen bonds C−H···S (for 9) and N−H···N (for 10), 2D layer-like supramolecular networks are constructed. In addition, the photoluminescent properties of two ligands as well as 11 compounds were also studied.

Introduction

Tridentate and tetradentate ligands such as salen- or pyridine-type unsymmetrical Schiff bases are capable of forming complexes with certain metal ions which can exhibit unusual coordination, high thermodynamic stability, and kinetic inertness. The coordination geometry of these complexes depends upon the coordination characteristics of donor atoms in different ligand arms, and coordination ability of counteranions and bridging ligands, as well as the reaction temperature and solvents, etc. Schiff bases are important systems in asymmetric catalysis and their transition metal complexes can often mimic biological sites; therefore, they are of great interest as enzyme models. Their five- and six-coordinated complexes can display a variety of structural, antibacterial activities, and fluorescent properties.

elements.content: The development of chelating agents is essential for the treatment of cadmium intoxication. The practical importance of Cd(II) coordination chemistry results from the mobilization and immobilization of this metal in the environment, in organisms, and in some technical processes that depend significantly on the complexation of the metal center by chelating organic molecules containing nitrogen and/or sulfur donor atoms. Complexes of Cd(II) with nitrogen-containing ligands have also been used successfully in ligand exchange chromatography. Though cadmium has been known as a toxic metal and is often associated with Hg and Pb as biologically harmful metal ions, recently it has been found that Cd(II) ion can served as the catalytic center in a newly discovered carbonic anhydrase. Cd(II) ion is capable of adopting a wide variety of geometries and coordination numbers permitted by its d10 configuration. Most Cd(II) complexes are octahedral, while four-, five-, seven-, and eight-coordinated complexes are limited to a few cases imposed either by bulkiness of the donor atoms or by steric requirements of the ligands. Moreover, the d10 center metals such as Cd(II) associated with the conjugated π systems containing aromatic rings favor the development of fluorescent and antibacterial materials.

Recently, we have also prepared two tridentate unsymmetrical Schiff base ligands 2-((2-(dimethylamino)ethylimino)methyl)phenol (HL 1 ) and methyl-2-pyridylmethylidenehy-drazinecarbodithioate (HL 2 ) (Scheme ), and X-ray single crystal diffraction shows their Zn(II), Ni(II), and Co(II) complexes are mononuclear compounds. In continuation, a series of new cadmium complexes have been synthesized and characterized by using the N2O/N2S donor tridentate unsymmetrical Schiff base ligands HL 1−2 . While compared with aforementioned cases containing unsymmetrical Schiff base ligands, fewer efforts have been devoted to the systematic investigation of Cd(II) coordination chemistry up to now.

Experimental Section

Physical Measurements

All materials were reagent grade obtained from commercial sources and used without further purification; solvents were dried by standard procedures. Ligands HL  1-2  were prepared according to the reported procedure. Elemental analyses for C, H, N were performed on a Perkin-Elmer 240C analytical instrument. IR spectra were recorded on a Nicolet FT-IR-170SX spectrophotometer in KBr pellets. The mass spectra (FAB-MS) were recorded on a ZAB-HS spectrometer. The luminescent spectra for the solid state were recorded at room temperature on Hitachi F-2500 and Edinburgh-FLS-920 with a xenon arc lamp as the light source. In the measurements of emission and excitation spectroscopy, the pass width is 5.0 nm. Thermal analyses (under oxygenated atmosphere, heating rate of 5 °C/min) were carried out in a Labsys NETZSCH TG 209 Setaram apparatus.

elements.content: The mononuclear complexes 1−4 were always obtained by reaction of Cd(ClO4)2·6H2O/Cd(ClO4)2·6H2O with L− (molar ratio = 1:2, where L = L1 (1 and 3) or L2 (2 and 4)) in the temperature range of 25−100 °C. The analytical data for four complexes 1−4 are in good agreement with the calculated values, though the single crystal of compound 1 has not been obtained. At the same range of temperature, reaction of equimolar CdCl2 with ligands L1−2 respectively gave mononuclear compound 5 and dinuclear compound 6. Similarly, the reaction of Cd(NO3)2 with ligands L1 gave dinuclear compound 7. However, the reaction of Cd(NO3)2 with ligands L2 has some differences; namely, at 25−60 °C, the product is compound 8 with coordinated methanol molecules, and on warming up to 100 °C, compound 8a with coordinated water molecules is obtained. With the replacement of Cd(CH3COO)2/Cd(ClO4)2 salts by mixtures of Cd(CH3COO)2/Cd(ClO4)2 + KSCN in the above reactions, the resulting complexes 9 and 10 present 1D chain-like structures. Obviously, the reactions with cadmium(II) salts have been shown to be very interesting in that, depending on the nature of the counteranions and reaction temperature for preparation of the complexes, several different types of cadmium(II) complexes were obtained (Scheme ).

elements.content: The IR spectra of HL 1−2 and the corresponding complexes 1−10 provide information about the metal−ligand bonding. The assignments are based on the typical group frequencies. A weak broadband in the region 3251−3348 cm−1 due to a hydrogen bonded OH group in free Schiff base ligand HL 1 was not observed in the infrared spectra of 1, 6, 7, or 9. This indicates that the phenolic oxygen is deprotonated and coordinated in four complexes. The strong ν(CN) bands occurring in the range 1635−1658 cm−1 for these complexes are shifted considerably toward lower frequencies compared to that of the free Schiff base ligand HL 1 (1650 cm−1), showing that the azomethine nitrogen atom is also coordinated to the metal. Weak band in the region 471−476 cm−1 for both complexes can be assigned to ν(M-O), and provides further evidence for coordination through the deprotonated phenolic oxygen atoms. As for compounds 2, 4, 5, 8, 8a, and 10, the IR spectrum of the free ligand HL2 in KBr does not exhibit a ν(SH) band at 2705 cm−1, but shows a broad and weak band at 3160 cm−1 attributable to ν(NH), indicating that in the solid state it remains as the thione form, the infrared spectra of which are consistent with its structural data given in Supporting Information of this paper (). However, in solution and in the presence of cadmium(II) salts, it quickly converts to the thiol form and coordinates to the metal ion in its deprotonated thiolate form, which is substantiated by the disappearance of the corresponding bands for ν(SH) and ν(NH) in 2, 6, 8, 8a, and 10. There are examples of metal-/thiosemicarbazone complexes in which the thiosemicarbazone ligands have been found to coordinate to a metal ion in their thiolate forms in our previous papers. To our knowledge, there has not been any example of a metal complex of a Schiff base ligand derived from a S-alkyl ester of thioamide function group in which a neutral protonated form of the ligand has been found. Our attempts to isolate cadmium(II) complexes of the neutral protonated form of HL2 have also been unsuccessful.

elements.content: The thiocyanate ion is known to coordinate to metal ions in different modes, and IR spectroscopy has proved an effective method of distinguishing between these modes. Complexes containing N-bonded thiocyanate exhibit a C−N stretching frequency generally in the 2040-/2080 cm−1 range, and S-bonded complexes exhibit this frequency in the 2080−2120 cm−1 range. As bridging ligands, the NCS− anions can also link a pair of metal ions in either an end-on (μ-1,1) via either the sulfur end or the nitrogen end or a side-on (μ-1,3) bonded manner. The IR spectra of end-on S-bridged thiocyanato-complexes, whose structures have been determined by X-ray diffraction, have been shown to exhibit only one C−N stretching band at approximately 2091 cm−1. The side-on NCS bridging mode (μ-1,3) has been found to be most common for copper(II) complexes. Thus, the spectrum of the polymeric [Cu(bpm)(NCS)] n complex (bpm = bipyrimidine), whose structure has been determined by X-ray crystallography, displays two C−N bands at 2120 and 2100 cm−1. For the present cadmium(II) complex [CdL2(NCS)2] n (10), the presence of two C−N bands at 2096 and 2060 cm−1 in its IR spectrum suggests that the thiocyanate ions are coordinated to the cadmium(II) ion as bridging ligands in a side-on manner, the complex being a μ-1,3 linked polymer. On the other hand, IR spectrum of compound [Cd2(L1)2]·(SCN)2] n (9) exhibits a strong unsplit C−N band at 2073 cm−1 and another two bands at 2078 and 2035 cm−1 indicating that the thiocyanate ion is coordinated to the cadmium(II) ion by two coordination forms, namely, as a unidentate ligand via the nitrogen atom and as bridging ligands in a side-on manner. This mode of bonding of the NCS− ion in the complex 10 has also been confirmed by X-ray crystallography (Vide Section of Structural discussion). In addition, for 3 and 4, the IR absorption bands at 1117−1123 and 627−631 cm−1 belong to the ClO4 − ions suggesting no coordination to the metal ion. elements.clean_text: The thiocyanate ion is known to coordinate to metal ions in different modes, and IR spectroscopy has proved an effective method of distinguishing between these modes. Complexes containing N-bonded thiocyanate exhibit a C-N stretching frequency generally in the 2040-/2080 cm-1 range, and S-bonded complexes exhibit this frequency in the 2080-2120 cm-1 range. As bridging ligands, the NCS- anions can also link a pair of metal ions in either an end-on (μ-1,1) via either the sulfur end or the nitrogen end or a side-on (μ-1,3) bonded manner. The IR spectra of end-on S-bridged thiocyanato-complexes, whose structures have been determined by X-ray diffraction, have been shown to exhibit only one C-N stretching band at approximately 2091 cm-1. The side-on NCS bridging mode (μ-1,3) has been found to be most common for copper(II) complexes. Thus, the spectrum of the polymeric [Cu(bpm)(NCS)] n  complex (bpm = bipyrimidine), whose structure has been determined by X-ray crystallography, displays two C-N bands at 2120 and 2100 cm-1. For the present cadmium(II) complex [CdL2(NCS)2] n  (10), the presence of two C-N bands at 2096 and 2060 cm-1 in its IR spectrum suggests that the thiocyanate ions are coordinated to the cadmium(II) ion as bridging ligands in a side-on manner, the complex being a μ-1,3 linked polymer. On the other hand, IR spectrum of compound [Cd2(L1)2]⋅(SCN)2] n  (9) exhibits a strong unsplit C-N band at 2073 cm-1 and another two bands at 2078 and 2035 cm-1 indicating that the thiocyanate ion is coordinated to the cadmium(II) ion by two coordination forms, namely, as a unidentate ligand via the nitrogen atom and as bridging ligands in a side-on manner. This mode of bonding of the NCS- ion in the complex 10 has also been confirmed by X-ray crystallography (Vide Section of Structural discussion). elements.content: The individual CdII centers in this molecule have slightly distorted octahedral geometries completed by two molecules of the coordinated tridentate ligands, each contributing a set of N, N and O donor atoms. For the geometry around the Cd(1) center, the trans angles O(1)−Cd(1)−N(2), O(2)−Cd(1)−N(4), and N(1)−Cd(1)−N(3) are 154.0(2), 152.5(2), and 176.5(2)°, respectively. Corresponding angles related to the Cd(2) center are 153.4(2), 149.9(2), and 174.9(2)°, respectively. The bond angles between the cis ligands and the Cd(1) center ranged from 80.9(2) to 152.5(2)°, the corresponding range for the Cd(2) center being 79.6(2)−109.0(2)°. The average Cd−N (2.340 Å) and Cd−O bond distances (2.322 Å) are not exceptional. The average C−O phen bond distance of 1.345 Å indicates the existence of phenolate ligand and not the phenoxyl radical form. Of particular interests are the Cd−O phen distances in this molecule which vary in a quite narrow range, viz. 2.283(5)−2.341(5) Å (Table ), that probably indicates identical electronic environment surrounding all the phenoxo O atoms, be in the protonated or in the deprotonated forms. The extra proton of the LH- ligand is equally shared by both forms of the ligand, thus generating a unique hydrogen-bonded structure with two almost identical Cd(II) centers. A similar type of dimeric structure has been reported recently for a cobalt(II) compound (Et4N)[Co(mp)(Hmp)](H2mp) = 2-mercapto-phenol) where each Co(II) center has tetrahedral geometry joined together with analogous O−H−O hydrogen bonds.

elements.content: From the above descriptions and discussions, the choice of anions is clearly critical in determining the molecular structures of the resultant complexes 1−10. Hence, it should be interesting and essential to compare the effect of the anions in these CdII complexes. In the current study, the nature (coordinating ability, size, donor character, etc.) of the anions is the underlying reason behind the differences in the structure of this series of CdII complexes. As shown in Scheme , in complexes 1−4, the anions ClO4 − and CH3COO− have weak coordination ability with metal ions, and thus they do not coordinate with CdII ion, or serve as counteranions and appear in crystal lattice, resulting in the formation of mononuclear compounds 1−4 (Figures , , and ). For complexes 5−8, the chloride and nitrate anions have strong coordination ability and usually present terminal coordination fashion; accordingly, the present compounds 5−8 are almost dinuclear, in which two terminal coordinating nitrate anions are in the same direction for 5−8 and a different one for 8a with reference to the plane of the core four-membered rings Cd2O2 and Cd2S2, respectively. On the other hand, the folding effect of the sulfur atom in ligand L2 also plays a certain role in the process of the construction of compounds 1−8. Furthermore, because thiocyanate anion may display flexible coordination modes, such as bridging- or terminal-ligating to CdII in present study, compounds 9 and 10 exhibit 1D chain structures (Figures and ).

elements.content: Metal−organic polymers have been reported to have abilities to affect the emission wavelength and intensity of the organic material through metal coordination. Therefore, it is important to investigate the luminescent properties of metal−organic polymers in view of potential applications. The photoluminescent behaviors of polymers 1−10 and free ligand L1−2 are studied in the solid state at room temperature. The emission spectra of 1−10 and L1−2 are depicted in Figures and . Apparently, the emission spectra of the complexes 1, 3, 6, 7, 9 and 2, 4, 5, 8, 8a, 10 respectively, resemble that of the ligands L1−2 excluding the emission intensity, indicating the fluorescence of the complexes 1−10 are L-based emission. Meanwhile, the green emission for the complexes 1−10 and L1−2 can be observed, where the maximum emission wavelength is at 553, 538 nm (under 370 nm excitation) for the ligands L1 and L2, 559, 562, 564, 561, and 562 nm (under 371 nm excitation) for the complexes 1, 3, 6, 7 an 9; 543, 544, 548, 549, 548, and 551 nm (under 373 nm excitation) for the complexes 2, 4, 5, 8, 8a, and 10. Compared with the emission spectra of the corresponding ligands L1 and L2, slightly red shifts of 6 nm in 1, 5 nm in 2, 9 nm in 3 and 6 nm in 4, 10 nm in 5, 11 nm in 6, 8 nm in 7, 11 nm in 8, 10 nm in 8a, 9 nm in 9, and 15 nm in 10 have been given, which are considered to mainly arise from the coordination of metal atom to ligand. The incorporation of Cd(II) effectively increases the conformational rigidity of ligand and reduces the loss of energy via vibration motions. Thus, the enhanced fluorescence intensities of the 11 complexes are detected, which open up the opportunity for photochemical applications of these complexes. Moreover, from Figures and , we find that the fluorescent intensities of the complexes 7, 8, 8a, 9, and 10 are stronger than those of other complexes, and it is a possible explanation that there is big conformational rigidity not only for 3D supramolecular network constructed by the cooperative association of coordination interactions as well as hydrogen bonds N−H···N and π···π packing interactions compared with those of other complexes, but also for the solid-state dinuclear complexes 7−8 with chelating coordinated nitrates. As for 9 and 10, the big conformational rigidity may be attributed to their own 1D framework structure.

In summary, nine 0D containing five mononuclear and four dinuclear, as well as two 1D metal−organic coordination polymers have been successfully synthesized from CdII salts and two unsymmetrical Schiff base ligands L1−2 under conventional solution or solvothermal reaction conditions and structurally characterized by X-ray diffraction analyses. Conclusion

In summary, nine 0D containing five mononuclear and four dinuclear, as well as two 1D metal-organic coordination polymers have been successfully synthesized from CdII salts and two unsymmetrical Schiff base ligands L1-2  under conventional solution or solvothermal reaction conditions and structurally characterized by X-ray diffraction analyses. Obviously, this systematic study clearly indicates the important role that the coordination ability and bulk of the counteranions can play in crystal engineering. Meanwhile, this work may provide a potential route for constructing low-dimensional framework architectures with different topological characters by selecting appropriate counteranions and functional organic ligands. Moreover, compared with ligand L1-2, the complexes 1-10 exhibit stronger solid-state fluorescence properties at room temperature.

In all complexes of 1−10, only complexes 4, 8, and 8a contain solvent molecules, and thus they were selected for the thermogravimetric analysis (TGA) to examine the thermal stability of the compounds (). TGA curve under nitrogen shows that the solid-state structure of 4 is highly robust. For 4, the lattice water molecule was lost in the approximate temperature from 95 to 152 °C (calcd 2.76%, found 2.69%). A complicated decomposition reaction then took place when the heating continued to 322 °C. In compound 8, it can be seen from its TG curve that two coordinated methanol molecules were lost in the approximate temperature from 155 to 228 °C (calcd. 7.68%, found 7.79%). Then a complicated decomposition reaction took place when the heating continued to 356 °C, while the preliminary TG analysis of 8a shows a weight loss below 278 °C (calcd. 4.47%, found 4.62% for two coordinated water molecules) in 8a and the coordination framework decomposition until a temperature up to 365 °C for 8a. Compared with 4, 8, and 8a, water or methanol molecules in 8 and 8a had a higher loss temperature deriving from its coordination to metal ions.

Luminescent Properties

Metal−organic polymers have been reported to have abilities to affect the emission wavelength and intensity of the organic material through metal coordination. Therefore, it is important to investigate the luminescent properties of metal−organic polymers in view of potential applications. The photoluminescent behaviors of polymers 1−10 and free ligand L1−2 are studied in the solid state at room temperature. The emission spectra of 1−10 and L1−2 are depicted in Figures and . Apparently, the emission spectra of the complexes 1, 3, 6, 7, 9 and 2, 4, 5, 8, 8a, 10 respectively, resemble that of the ligands L1−2 excluding the emission intensity, indicating the fluorescence of the complexes 1−10 are L-based emission. Meanwhile, the green emission for the complexes 1−10 and L1−2 can be observed, where the maximum emission wavelength is at 553, 538 nm (under 370 nm excitation) for the ligands L1 and L2, 559, 562, 564, 561, and 562 nm (under 371 nm excitation) for the complexes 1, 3, 6, 7 an 9; 543, 544, 548, 549, 548, and 551 nm (under 373 nm excitation) for the complexes 2, 4, 5, 8, 8a, and 10. Compared with the emission spectra of the corresponding ligands L1 and L2, slightly red shifts of 6 nm in 1, 5 nm in 2, 9 nm in 3 and 6 nm in 4, 10 nm in 5, 11 nm in 6, 8 nm in 7, 11 nm in 8, 10 nm in 8a, 9 nm in 9, and 15 nm in 10 have been given, which are considered to mainly arise from the coordination of metal atom to ligand. The incorporation of Cd(II) effectively increases the conformational rigidity of ligand and reduces the loss of energy via vibration motions. Thus, the enhanced fluorescence intensities of the 11 complexes are detected, which open up the opportunity for photochemical applications of these complexes. Moreover, from Figures and , we find that the fluorescent intensities of the complexes 7, 8, 8a, 9, and 10 are stronger than those of other complexes, and it is a possible explanation that there is big conformational rigidity not only for 3D supramolecular network constructed by the cooperative association of coordination interactions as well as hydrogen bonds N−H···N and π···π packing interactions compared with those of other complexes, but also for the solid-state dinuclear complexes 7−8 with chelating coordinated nitrates. As for 9 and 10, the big conformational rigidity may be attributed to their own 1D framework structure.
